726411f-a.text:
Corona Avenue, north side, at (right partially shown ) and adjoining 90th Street (right not shown. E.L. Armbruster states that one Van Rieper states the fully seen house as that of Mrs. Riker. However a map compiled by J. Riker Junior in 1852 shows a house adjoining the African Church but gives no owner. In 1873, one Braddish was an occupant but no owner is listed in 1909
or 1915.
1922
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

726410f-b.text:
Corona Avenue, north side, east of 90th Street, showing St. Marks African M.E. Church and Cemetery. The African Church as it was originally known was established in 1828 on donated property. It was repaired in 1925. The bodies lying in the cemetery surrounding the chrch were removed from there to Mount Olivet Cemetery about 1930. Now a series of two story buildings
stand in the former cemetery grounds.
Fen. 1924.
Views 1 & 2
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection
